  "answer": "**No direct relation is stated in the corpus between metrical form (śloka/verse vs. prose) and legal content.**\n\nManu (*Manusmṛti*) and Yājñavalkya (*Yājñavalkya Smṛti*) are entirely in verse (śloka layout across all chapters), covering broad *dharma* including legal procedure (*vyavahāra*), inheritance, debts, assault, and royal duties.[^1][^2] Viṣṇu (*Viṣṇu Smṛti*) is also verse-based (e.g., chapters 6–7 on debts/documents), though user observation notes prose-verse mix (not contradicted in sampled chapters).[^3] Nārada (*Nārada Smṛti*) is prose (explicit layout), focusing intensely on *vyavahāra* (e.g., 18 topics like debts, deposits, witnesses, ordeals).[^4]\n\nThe corpus shows no explicit discussion linking form to content (e.g., verse for mnemonic ethics vs. prose for judicial precision). Patterns suggest verse suits comprehensive *smṛti* (Manu/Yājñavalkya/Viṣṇu), prose a procedural handbook (Nārada). Searches for \"sloka/prose/verse\" yield no meta-analysis.[^5]\n\n[^1]: *Manusmṛti*, Ch. 8, [translation/](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/).\n[^2]: *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, Chs. 1–3, [translation/](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-47ada8) (Ch.1); [Ch.2](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/02/translation/#p-d2bcad).\n[^3]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, Ch. 6 [translation/](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/06/translation/#p-423115); Ch.7 [translation/](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/07/translation/#p-08aad7).\n[^4]: *Nārada Smṛti*, Ch. 1, [translation/](https://falsafa.corpus/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-287f20).\n[^5]: Corpus search \"sloka OR verse OR prose... Manu OR Yajnavalkya OR Vishnu OR Narada\" yields incidental mentions (e.g., *Manusmṛti* 1.35 names Nārada; *Kātyāyana Smṛti* cites Manu), no form-content analysis.",
